The decline in economic activity has resulted in a continuous increase in unemployment in the state by November. According to the National Institute for Statistics and Geography, the level of unemployment in the state has been recorded during the first three quarters of increased growth. From January to March 55,053 people of the State of Sinaloa, which represents a level of unemployment of 4,53% of economically active population. In the second quarter, unemployment increased to 5,28% and between July and August, average unemployment continued to grow and reached 6,19%, which represents approximately 74,000 unemployed people.
Less Liquidity
For unemployment during the year in the state of Sinaloa, more factors can be explained. According to Gerard Löpez Cervantes, the Director of the UAS Economic and Social Science Faculty may explain indirectly, on the basis of the steps carried out at the public policy level.
"We are witnesses of increasing unemployment, which relates to various factors, among them is the loss of liquidity on the market because of the restriction of resources due to the legislation approved by the Congress in the fight against laundering of dirty money. It is not easy for people who are illegally enriched in dollars to earn, invest them or use them for something," he stressed.
Suspension of migration
Lopez Cervantes stated that demographic factor is also involved in unemployment growth.
"The number of people who go to work for abroad, to the United States, has decreased, however, because of the reasons of an inadequate entry and then because even when these people get out of the border, it is difficult to get job for them. Thus, people stay and require work from our state, and so unemployment grows," he said.
Incompliance
Analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa also deteriorates because of the growing insecurity that prevails in the field of work. According to the National Institute for Statistics and Democracy, 60.38% of employees in the state work without taking the doses of the social security management.
Other features of the labour market, such as low wages, are added to unemployment and independence. In this administrative territory, the lowest wages from the country are listed in the Mexican Institute for Social Security and the Secretariat of Work and Social Planning.
The average monthly income of workers in the state of Sinaloa was deeply under the national average of 7 375 pesets by September.
Reduction of direct foreign investments
In addition to the decline in economic activity and the increase of unemployment in 2011, the highest decline in foreign direct investment has also been recorded in the past 10 years. According to the Ministry of Finance between January and June, direct foreign investments of $630,697 were achieved by 87,74% compared to $5,143,312 for the same period in the previous year.
